;Digital Inclusion means promoting diversity
Taguri tumḍint temmal-d asmil n tiggwti


;For the Internet to fulfill its greatest promise, it must reflect the diversity and experience of all people, everywhere.
Akken Internet ad yeṭṭef lweɛd-is, yessefk ad d-imudd udem n tanḍa akked tarmit i yemdanen meṛṛa, di yal amḍiq deg umaḍal.


;As inclusive as the Web can seem, it’s not yet an equal playing field. More than half the world is still without it; emerging economies and marginalized communities are often the last to gain access. Far fewer women are using the Internet than men. And without diversity among its creators, the Web itself will reflect unconscious biases, while personalizing algorithms can reinforce our own.
Ɣas akken Web yettban d imegri, weǧin yella d annar n wurar arawsan. ugar n uzgen deg umaḍal ttidiren s war Internet, tidamsiwin d-iṭallayen akked timezdagnutin yuɣen tama dima d ineggura i yekeččmen. Drus n tlawin i yesseqdacen Internet ma nmuqel ar yirgazen. Ur nettaf ara tanḍa gar imenulfuyen, Web ima-is yettban s yir tamuɣli, di lawan anida ilguritmen yettmuddun udem zemren ad tessiǧhidden wid-nneɣ.


;In nine developing countries, women are still nearly 50% less likely to access the Internet than men.
Di tza n tmura yettnernin, mazal ur yewwiḍ ara  50%  n tilawin i yezmren ad kecment ar Internet am yirgazen.


;Source: <a href="%(wwwf)s">World Wide Web Foundation</a>, 2015
Aɣbalu: <a href="%(wwwf)s">Tasbeddit World Wide Web</a>, 2015


